      "## Children's Day Speech Guide",

      "### For Students Giving a Speech",
      "A strong Children's Day speech avoids the temptation to recite facts about Nehru that every other speech also recites. Instead, it tells a personal story:",
      "1. **Open with a memory** — 'Last year on Children's Day, my classmate Rohan said something in the talent show that nobody expected. He did not perform. He just told us about his grandfather's childhood in a village with no school. That one-minute story was the most memorable thing all day.'",
      "2. **Connect to what childhood means** — 'Childhood is not one thing. For some of us, it is full of sports and hobbies. For others, it is full of responsibilities that feel too old for our age. Children's Day should acknowledge both.'",
      "3. **Name specific classmates** — 'I want to appreciate Meera for always sharing her lunch, Dev for explaining maths with more patience than any textbook, and Anjali whose drawings make our classroom walls worth looking at.'",
      "4. **Close with a commitment** — 'The best way to celebrate Children's Day is to be kinder to each other tomorrow, not just today.'",

      "### Delivery Tips for Young Speakers",
