    content: [
      "At my cousin Radhika's wedding last December, the family hired a calligrapher to write names on the gift envelopes. Beautiful, professional envelopes that made every card look like it cost a thousand rupees. I watched her open thirty-seven cards over two days. Most had some variation of 'Congratulations! Wishing you a lifetime of happiness!' written inside — pleasant, forgettable, interchangeable. Then she opened one from her college roommate Divya which read: 'Radhi — remember when we were 19 and you told me you would never get married because marriage seemed boring? Well, I watched you and Karthik today and I have never seen you look less bored in my life. You found someone who makes your eyes do that thing. I am so happy I want to cry. Congratulations, you stubborn, wonderful person.' Radhika read it twice, laughed until she teared up, and immediately called Divya. That card did not follow any etiquette template. It did not need to. It was written by someone who knew her — and it showed.",

      "That is the gap this article is about. Most wedding wishes are written to satisfy an obligation. The good ones are written to reach a person. The difference is not talent or vocabulary. It is specificity — knowing something real about the couple and letting that knowledge shape the message. A wedding wish that could be printed in a store-bought card without any editing is, by definition, generic. A wedding wish that could only be sent from you to this particular couple is, by definition, personal. This article will help you write the personal kind — across every relationship, format, and cultural context.",

      "## Why Wedding Messages Matter More Than You Think",

      "### The Card That Gets Kept",
      "Couples receive dozens to hundreds of messages during their wedding season. Research from the Gottman Institute on relationship psychology suggests that specific positive statements — ones that reference particular qualities or shared memories — carry more emotional weight than general blessings. The couple may not remember who sent the company-approved congratulations email. They will remember who wrote about the specific moment they knew the couple was right for each other. Wedding cards are one of the few tangible artefacts of the event that couples keep for years. Albums fade, flowers die, videographers deliver late. The handwritten card stays in a drawer and gets reread on anniversaries. What that card says determines whether rereading it brings a smile or a shrug.",

      "### The Social Intelligence Factor",
      "Matching your tone to your relationship is not being artificial. It is social intelligence — the ability to read context and respond appropriately. A formal message from your boss feels respectful. A formal message from your childhood best friend feels distant. Same words, different effect. The best wedding messages calibrate three variables: emotional closeness (how well you know them), formality of the occasion (intimate gathering vs. grand reception), and cultural context (family traditions, religious elements, regional customs). Getting this calibration right is what separates a message that connects from one that merely follows convention.",

      "## The Wedding Wish Formula",

      "### Three Lines That Always Work",
      "If you need a reliable structure — especially when you are pressed for time — use this three-line formula:",
      "- **Line 1: Congratulations + names** — Always use the couple's names. 'Congratulations, Karthik and Radhika' is already warmer than 'Congratulations to the happy couple.'",
      "- **Line 2: One specific quality or wish** — Name something real. 'Your patience with each other during that long-distance year told everyone this was built to last.'",
      "- **Line 3: A forward blessing** — 'Wishing your home a lifetime of the kind of laughter I saw at your engagement party.'",

      "### Why the Middle Line Is Everything",
      "Without Line 2, your message is a greeting card. With it, your message is a gift. The specific observation — whether it is a quality you admire, a memory you share, or a moment you witnessed — is what transforms a generic wish into a personal one. You do not need to be poetic. You just need to be honest about one thing you have noticed about this particular couple. Even something as simple as 'I love how you two always finish each other's stories without getting annoyed' tells the couple that someone was paying attention to their relationship — and that what they have is visible and valued.",

      "## Wedding Wishes by Relationship",

      "### For Parents (to Son or Daughter)",
      "'We have loved you for [age] years, and today we are not losing you — we are gaining another person to love. Karthik, welcome to this family. You already feel like ours. To both of you: build something beautiful, be patient with each other, and know that this home is always open.'",
      "'Beta, watching you today reminded me of the day you were born — both times, I could not stop crying. You have found someone who sees you the way we have always seen you: as someone extraordinary. Be happy. We are so proud.'",

      "### For a Sibling",
      "'Bhai — I cannot believe the kid who used to steal my food is getting married before me. Honestly, all jokes aside, watching you with [partner's name] makes me genuinely happy. You are calmer, kinder, and you laugh more. That is how I know this is right. Love you. Do not make me say it again at the reception.'",
      "'Di, you were my first example of what strength looks like. Now I get to watch you build a partnership that matches that strength. [Partner's name] is lucky. But honestly, so are you. Congratulations.'",

      "### For a Close Friend",
      "'I have known you since [year/context]. I have seen you nervous, confident, heartbroken, and ridiculous. And I have never seen you the way you are with [partner's name] — settled. Not boring-settled. Happy-settled. The kind where you stop looking. Congratulations. You deserve every good thing.'",
      "'Remember [specific shared memory]? I think that was the first time you mentioned [partner's name]. You tried to be casual about it and failed completely. Your face gave you away then, and it gave you away today at the altar. I am so happy for you. Let us celebrate properly this weekend.'",

      "### For a Colleague or Professional Contact",
      "'Congratulations on your marriage, [Name]. Wishing you and [partner] a lifetime of mutual support and shared joy. It has been a pleasure working alongside someone who brings the same care to their personal life as they do to their professional work. Enjoy every moment of this celebration.'",
      "'[Name], warmest congratulations on your wedding. May this new chapter bring you balance, happiness, and all the good things you both deserve. Looking forward to hearing about the honeymoon adventures.'",

      "### For an Acquaintance or Distant Relative",
      "'Congratulations and warmest wishes to you both. May your marriage be filled with love, laughter, and lasting partnership. Wishing you a beautiful journey together.'",
      "This is the one context where shorter and more general is perfectly appropriate. An acquaintance sending a deeply personal message would feel intrusive. Elegance and brevity serve this relationship better.",

      "### For Interfaith or Cross-Cultural Weddings",
      "'Watching two families and two traditions come together today was genuinely moving. Your marriage is not just about two people — it is about two worlds choosing each other. May the best of both cultures fill your home, your kitchen, and your conversations. Congratulations.'",

      "### For a Second Marriage",
      "'Congratulations, [Name]. What I admire about you is that you did not let the past make you cynical — you stayed open, and look what walked in. [Partner's name] is wonderful, and you deserve this happiness. Enjoy every bit of it.'",
      "For second marriages, avoid referencing the previous marriage. Focus on what is present, not what came before. Joy, courage, and openness are the right notes.",

      "## Wedding Card Etiquette — The Practical Guide",

      "### Handwritten vs. Digital",
      "A handwritten card in the wedding gift envelope remains the gold standard. The physical act of writing conveys effort that digital text cannot replicate. However, [digital greeting cards](/create) are entirely appropriate for destination weddings you could not attend, international couples, and situations where your gift is arriving by delivery. A well-designed digital card with a personal message outperforms a generic physical card every time. The medium matters less than the message.",

      "### How Long Should a Wedding Message Be?",
      "- **Close family**: 4–8 sentences. Emotional depth and personal reference are expected and welcomed.",
      "- **Close friends**: 3–6 sentences. Warmth plus one specific memory or observation.",
      "- **Colleagues**: 2–4 sentences. Professional warmth without personal oversharing.",
      "- **Acquaintances**: 1–3 sentences. Simple, elegant, genuine.",
      "The most common mistake is writing too much for distant relationships and too little for close ones. Recalibrate: invest your best writing where you are emotionally closest.",

      "### What to Write When You Do Not Know the Partner",
      "This happens frequently — a friend announces a wedding and you have never met their partner. Your message should welcome the partner warmly without pretending familiarity: 'Congratulations! I have not had the chance to meet [partner's name] yet, but anyone who makes you this happy is someone I already like. Looking forward to meeting them properly. Wishing you both a beautiful life together.'",

      "## Wedding Messages Across Indian Cultures",

      "### Hindu Weddings",
      "Hindu wedding wishes often invoke blessings of prosperity, harmony, and divine grace. Phrases like 'May your journey together be blessed with love and dharma' or 'Wishing you a saat-janm partnership of trust and friendship' resonate with the cultural context of the saat pheras. If you know the specific tradition (Tamil Brahmin, Marwari, Bengali, South Indian), referencing a specific ritual adds warmth: 'May the mangalsutra always remind you of the promises you made today.'",

      "### Muslim Weddings (Nikah)",
      "Nikah messages often include blessings from the Quran. A respectful wish might read: 'May Allah bless your nikah with sakinah (tranquillity), mawaddah (love), and rahmah (mercy). Wishing you a marriage built on faith, patience, and mutual respect.' If you are not Muslim, a respectful secular message with warm blessings is perfectly appropriate — sincerity transcends religious boundaries.",

      "### Sikh Weddings (Anand Karaj)",
      "The Anand Karaj ceremony emphasises spiritual union. Messages can reference this: 'May your Anand Karaj be the beginning of a partnership rooted in faith, equality, and shared purpose. Waheguru bless your journey. Congratulations to both families.'",

      "### Christian Weddings",
      "Christian wedding wishes often invoke God's grace: 'May God bless your union with love, strength, and unwavering faith. Congratulations on this beautiful covenant.' For close friends, personal warmth combined with a blessing works well.",

      "### Multi-Faith or Non-Religious Weddings",
      "If the couple is not religious or the wedding is secular, focus on partnership values: trust, laughter, patience, growth, and shared purpose. Avoid assuming religious context when you are not sure. Universal blessings — 'Wishing you a home filled with peace and honest conversation' — work beautifully across every context.",

      "## Things to Avoid in Wedding Messages",

      "### The Definitive Don'ts",
      "- **Do not mention ex-partners.** Not even as a 'you finally found the right one' compliment. The implication that someone was the wrong one belongs nowhere near a wedding.",
      "- **Do not give unsolicited marriage advice.** 'Never go to bed angry' and 'Happy wife, happy life' are clichés that patronise. Advice is for private conversations years into the friendship, not greeting cards.",
      "- **Do not mention children or pregnancy.** 'Cannot wait for babies!' is pressure disguised as enthusiasm. The couple's reproductive choices are not public content.",
      "- **Do not make jokes about marriage being difficult.** 'Ball and chain' humour, 'say goodbye to freedom' jokes, and 'good luck, you will need it' comments undermine the day's significance. They are not funny. They are tired.",
      "- **Do not comment on finances.** 'What a beautiful venue — must have cost a fortune!' or 'I hope the wedding budget was worth it!' is never appropriate.",
      "- **Do not copy-paste.** If you are attending three weddings in one season, write three different messages. Couples compare notes. And even if they do not, writing the same line to three different people is a disservice to all three relationships.",
      "- **Do not make it about yourself.** 'When will it be my turn?' or launching into your own love story in someone else's wedding card is self-centred. Keep the focus on the couple.",

      "## Wedding Wishes for Specific Situations",

      "### When You Cannot Attend the Wedding",
      "'I am so sorry I could not be there today. Please know that even from [location], I am celebrating you. I can picture [specific detail about the couple or venue]. Congratulations to both of you. Save me a piece of cake and a full recap. Love you.'",

      "### For a Wedding Gift Accompanying a Group Gift",
      "'From all of us at [team/friend group] — congratulations! [One line of collective warmth]. Wishing you both a marriage as strong as the friendships that brought us here.'",

      "### For an Engagement Card (Pre-Wedding)",
      "'Congratulations on the engagement! I cannot wait to see what you two plan. Knowing you, it will be [one specific reference to their personality]. Enjoy every moment of this season.'",

      "### For a Wedding Anniversary (Using the Same Principles)",
      "'Happy anniversary to two people who make marriage look like a choice worth making every single day. [One specific observation about their partnership]. Here is to many more years of [quality you admire].'",

      "## How to Write a Short Wedding Speech",

      "### The 90-Second Formula",
      "If you are asked to speak at a reception, toast, or sangeet, use this structure:",
      "1. **Introduce yourself and your connection** — 'I am Sneha. I have known the bride since we were 12 and shared a bench in Class 7.'",
      "2. **One specific story about the person** — Not about the couple yet. One story that captures who your friend is. 'Radhika once spent three hours helping me rewrite a terrible essay. She did not fix it for me. She sat next to me and asked questions until I figured it out myself. That is who she is.'",
      "3. **How you know the partner is right** — 'The first time I met Karthik, he did the same thing. He asked her questions instead of trying to impress her. That is when I knew.'",
      "4. **The toast** — 'To Radhika and Karthik — may your patience with each other last longer than Radhika's patience with my essays. Congratulations.'",

      "### Delivery Tips",
      "- Keep it under two minutes. Brevity at weddings is a gift to everyone.",
      "- Speak to the couple, not the audience. Look at them.",
      "- If you cry, let it happen. Nobody minds. They probably will too.",
      "- Do not use the speech to announce your own news, roast the couple harshly, or reference inside jokes that exclude the room.",

      "## The Psychology of a Good Wedding Wish",

      "### Why Couples Remember Specific Messages",
      "The Gottman Institute's research on positive sentiment override shows that specific positive statements build stronger emotional bonds than general ones. When a message names a particular quality — 'your patience during the long-distance phase' rather than 'your amazing love' — it registers as observed evidence rather than performed politeness. The couple feels genuinely seen. This is why the card from someone who noticed a quiet, specific thing about the relationship often matters more than the most beautifully written generic blessing. You do not need to be a writer. You need to be an observer.",

      "### The Gift of Being Noticed",
      "Most couples experience their wedding day as a blur of logistics, emotions, and people. The messages they return to later — the ones they reread during quiet evenings — are the ones that make them feel like someone was truly present. Not just at the event, but in the [relationship between their everyday life and this celebration](/blog/importance-of-celebrating-festivals-together-with-loved-ones). Your message is your evidence of presence. Write it like you were there — not at the venue, but in the friendship.",

      "## FAQ About Wedding Wishes",
      "### What should I write in a wedding card?",
      "A strong wedding card has three elements: a congratulations line using the couple's names, one specific observation about their relationship or a shared memory, and a forward-looking blessing. Example: 'Congratulations, Karthik and Radhika. Your patience and kindness with each other is visible to everyone around you. Wishing your home a lifetime of the laughter I saw at your engagement party.' Keep the length appropriate to your closeness — 4-8 sentences for family, 2-4 for colleagues.",
      "### How do I write wedding wishes for someone I do not know well?",
      "For acquaintances or distant relatives, keep your message elegant and brief — 1 to 3 sentences. A simple 'Congratulations and warmest wishes to you both. May your marriage be filled with love, laughter, and lasting partnership' is perfectly appropriate. You do not need to manufacture familiarity. Sincerity at a shorter length is always better than forced personal detail with someone you barely know.",
      "### What should I avoid writing in a wedding message?",
      "Avoid mentioning ex-partners, making jokes about marriage being difficult, commenting on finances or the wedding budget, pressuring the couple about children, giving unsolicited advice, or copy-pasting the same message to multiple couples. Also avoid making the message about yourself. The card is the couple's moment. Keep the focus on them, their relationship, and your genuine good wishes.",
      "### Is it okay to send digital wedding wishes instead of a physical card?",
      "Yes. Digital wedding greetings are entirely appropriate for destination weddings you could not attend, international couples, or when your gift is arriving by delivery. A personalised digital card with a thoughtful message outperforms a generic store-bought card every time. The medium matters far less than the specificity and warmth of what you write inside it.",
      "### How long should a wedding speech be?",
      "Keep a wedding speech under two minutes — ideally 60 to 90 seconds. Use a simple structure: introduce yourself and your connection to the couple, share one specific story about the person you know, explain how you knew their partner was right for them, and close with a toast. Brevity at weddings is a gift to everyone in the room. Speak to the couple directly, not to the audience, and if genuine emotion comes through, let it."
    ]
